[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] An equivalent theorem for conical combinations states that if a point x lies in the conical hull $\mathrm {Cone} (P)$ of a set $P\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , then x can be written as the conical combination of at most d points in P .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Two other theorems of Helly and Radon are closely related to Carathéodory's theorem: the latter theorem can be used to prove the former theorems and vice versa.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The result is named for Constantin Carathéodory, who proved the theorem in 1911 for the case when P is compact.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] In 1914 Ernst Steinitz expanded Carathéodory's theorem for arbitrary sets.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Carathéodory's theorem in 2 dimensions states that we can construct a triangle consisting of points from *P* that encloses any point in the convex hull of *P*.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The convex hull of this set is a square.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] If $x\in \mathrm {Conv} (S)\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , then x is the convex sum of at most $d+1$ points of S .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The essence of Carathéodory's theorem is in the finite case.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] This reduction to the finite case is possible because $\mathrm {Conv} (S)$ is the set of *finite* convex combination of elements of S (see the convex hull page for details).
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The second part reduces to the first part by "lifting up one dimension", a common trick used to reduce affine geometry to linear algebra, and reduce convex bodies to convex cones.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] This induces an embedding of S into $S\times \{1\}\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d+1}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] If we can prove it for all $N=d+1$ , then by induction we have proved it for all $N\geq d+1$ .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Thus it remains to prove it for $N=d+1$ .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] If some $w_{n}=0$ , then the proof is finished.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Otherwise, let $\theta$ be the smallest $\theta$ such that one of $w_{n}+\theta w_{d+1}u_{n}=0$ .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Then we obtain a representation of x as a linear combination with non-negative coefficients, with at most d nonzero terms.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Alternative proofs use Helly's theorem or the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] For any nonempty $P\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , define its **Carathéodory's number** to be the smallest integer r , such that for any $x\in \mathrm {Conv} (P)$ , there exists a representation of x as a convex sum of up to r elements in P .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Carathéodory's theorem simply states that any nonempty subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ has Carathéodory's number $\leq d+1$ .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] This upper bound is not necessarily reached.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] For example, the unit sphere in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ has Carathéodory's number equal to 2, since any point inside the sphere is the convex sum of two points on the sphere.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] With additional assumptions on $P\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , upper bounds strictly lower than $d+1$ can be obtained.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Caratheodory's theorem type results where the diameter replaces the dependency on the dimension are well known.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] An explicit statement of a no-dimensional Caratheodory's theorem was provided by Barman.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] It is probable that this theorem was stated much earlier, as it is an easy consequence of the analysis of the Perceptron algorithm of Novikoff.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Specifically, for every positive integer r and every point within the convex hull of a finite point set P , there exists an r -point subset R such that the given point is within distance $\operatorname {diam} P/{\sqrt {2r}}$ of the convex hull of R .
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Let *X*1, ..., *X**d*+1 be sets in **R***d* and let *x* be a point contained in the intersection of the convex hulls of all these *d*+1 sets.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] By viewing the sets *X*1, ..., *X**d*+1 as different colors, the set *T* is made by points of all colors, hence the "colorful" in the theorem's name.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The set *T* is also called a *rainbow simplex*, since it is a *d*-dimensional simplex in which each corner has a different color.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] This theorem has a variant in which the convex hull is replaced by the conical hull.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Let *X*1, ..., *X**d* be sets in **R**d and let *x* be a point contained in the intersection of the *conical hulls* of all these *d* sets.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] Mustafa and Ray extended this colorful theorem from points to convex bodies.
[src:convex-geometry/carathéodory-s-theorem-convex-hull] The computational problem of finding the colorful set lies in the intersection of the complexity classes PPAD and PLS.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] In mathematics, **convex geometry** is the branch of geometry studying convex sets, mainly in Euclidean space.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] Convex sets occur naturally in many areas: computational geometry, convex analysis, discrete geometry, functional analysis, geometry of numbers, integral geometry, linear programming, probability theory, game theory, etc.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] (though only portions of the latter two are included in convex geometry).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] Convex geometry is a relatively young mathematical discipline.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] A big part of their results was soon generalized to spaces of higher dimensions, and in 1934 T.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] Fenchel gave a comprehensive survey of convex geometry in Euclidean space **R**n.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-geometry] Further development of convex geometry in the 20th century and its relations to numerous mathematical disciplines are summarized in the *Handbook of convex geometry* edited by P.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A **convex polytope** is a special case of a polytope, having the additional property that it is also a convex set contained in the n -dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Convex polytopes play an important role both in various branches of mathematics and in applied areas, most notably in linear programming.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Most texts use the term "polytope" for a bounded convex polytope, and the word "polyhedron" for the more general, possibly unbounded object (an *n*-dimensional polyhedron).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Others (including this article) allow polytopes to be unbounded.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The terms "bounded/unbounded convex polytope" will be used below whenever the boundedness is critical to the discussed issue.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Yet other texts identify a convex polytope with its boundary.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In the influential textbooks of Grünbaum and Ziegler on the subject, as well as in many other texts in discrete geometry, convex polytopes are often simply called "polytopes".
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Grünbaum points out that this is solely to avoid the endless repetition of the word "convex", and that the discussion should throughout be understood as applying only to the convex variety (p.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A polytope is called *full-dimensional* if it is an n -dimensional object in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Many examples of *bounded* convex polytopes can be found in convex polyhedra and convex polygon.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A convex polytope may be defined in a number of ways, depending on what is more suitable for the problem at hand.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Grünbaum's definition is in terms of a convex set of points in space.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Other important definitions are: as the intersection of half-spaces (half-space representation) and as the convex hull of a set of points (vertex representation).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] This is equivalent to defining a bounded convex polytope as the convex hull of a finite set of points, where the finite set must contain the set of extreme points of the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Such a definition is called a **vertex representation** (**V-representation** or **V-description**).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] For a compact convex polytope, the minimal V-description is unique and it is given by the set of the vertices of the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A convex polytope is called an integral polytope if all of its vertices have integer coordinates.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A convex polytope may be defined as an intersection of a finite number of half-spaces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Such definition is called a **half-space representation** (**H-representation** or **H-description**).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] There exist infinitely many H-descriptions of a convex polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] However, for a full-dimensional convex polytope, the minimal H-description is in fact unique and is given by the set of the facet-defining halfspaces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] where n is the dimension of the space containing the polytope under consideration.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] where m is the number of half-spaces defining the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] where A is an $m\times n$ matrix, x is an $n\times 1$ column vector whose coordinates are the variables $x_{1}$ to $x_{n}$ , and b is an $m\times 1$ column vector whose coordinates are the right-hand sides $b_{1}$ to $b_{m}$ of the scalar inequalities.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] An **open convex polytope** is defined in the same way, with strict inequalities used in the formulas instead of the non-strict ones.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The coefficients of each row of A and b correspond with the coefficients of the linear inequality defining the respective half-space.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Hence, each row in the matrix corresponds with a **supporting hyperplane** of the polytope, a hyperplane bounding a half-space that contains the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] If a supporting hyperplane also intersects the polytope, it is called a **bounding hyperplane** (since it is a supporting hyperplane, it can only intersect the polytope at the polytope's boundary).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The foregoing definition assumes that the polytope is full-dimensional.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In this case, there is a *unique* minimal set of defining inequalities (up to multiplication by a positive number).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Inequalities belonging to this unique minimal system are called **essential**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The set of points of a polytope which satisfy an essential inequality with equality is called a **facet**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] If the polytope is not full-dimensional, then the solutions of $Ax\leq b$ lie in a proper affine subspace of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and the polytope can be studied as an object in this subspace.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In this case, there exist linear equations which are satisfied by all points of the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Adding one of these equations to any of the defining inequalities does not change the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Therefore, in general there is no unique minimal set of inequalities defining the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In general the intersection of arbitrary half-spaces need not be bounded.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] However if one wishes to have a definition equivalent to that as a convex hull, then bounding must be explicitly required.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] By requiring that the intersection of half-spaces results in a bounded set, the definition becomes equivalent to the vertex-representation.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The *bounded* intersection of closed half-spaces of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is clearly compact and convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A compact and convex set with a finite number of extreme points must be a polytope, where those extreme points form the set of vertices.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Let $x\in {\textrm {ext}}(P)$ be an extreme point of $P:=\bigcap _{i=1}^{k}H_{i}$ , the bounded intersection of closed half-spaces $H_{i}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] We consider the intersection of all the corresponding hyperplanes (which divide the space into the half-spaces) that contain x .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] For each half-space where the hyperplane does not contain x , we consider the intersection of the *interior* of those half-spaces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Since x is an extreme point of P and $D:=U\cap O$ is relatively open, it follows that D must be 0-dimensional and $D=\left\{x\right\}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] If D was not 0-dimensional, x would be the inner point of (at least) a line, which contradicts x being an extreme point.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Since every construction of D chooses either the interior or the boundary of one of the k closed half-spaces, there are only finitely many different sets D .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Every extreme point lies in one of these sets, which means that the amount of extreme points is finite.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A subtle point in the representation by vectors is that the number of vectors may be exponential in the dimension, so the proof that a vector is in the polytope might be exponentially long.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Fortunately, Carathéodory's theorem guarantees that every vector in the polytope can be represented by at most *d*+1 defining vectors, where *d* is the dimension of the space.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] For an unbounded polytope (sometimes called: polyhedron), the H-description is still valid, but the V-description should be extended.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Theodore Motzkin (1936) proved that any unbounded polytope can be represented as a sum of a *bounded polytope* and a *convex polyhedral cone*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In other words, every vector in an unbounded polytope is a convex sum of its vertices (its "defining points"), plus a conical sum of the Euclidean vectors of its infinite edges (its "defining rays").
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] This is called the **finite basis theorem**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Every (bounded) convex polytope is the image of a simplex, as every point is a convex combination of the (finitely many) vertices.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] However, polytopes are not in general isomorphic to simplices.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] This is in contrast to the case of vector spaces and linear combinations, every finite-dimensional vector space being not only an image of, but in fact isomorphic to, Euclidean space of some dimension (or analog over other fields).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A **face** of a convex polytope is any intersection of the polytope with a halfspace such that none of the interior points of the polytope lie on the boundary of the halfspace.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Equivalently, a face is the set of points giving equality in some valid inequality of the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] If a polytope is *d*-dimensional, its facets are its (*d* − 1)-dimensional faces, its vertices are its 0-dimensional faces, its edges are its 1-dimensional faces, and its ridges are its (*d* − 2)-dimensional faces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Given a convex polytope *P* defined by the matrix inequality $Ax\leq b$ , if each row in *A* corresponds with a bounding hyperplane and is linearly independent of the other rows, then each facet of *P* corresponds with exactly one row of *A*, and vice versa, as long as equality holds.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Each point on a given facet will satisfy the linear equality of the corresponding row in the matrix.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] (It may or may not also satisfy equality in other rows).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Similarly, each point on a ridge will satisfy equality in two of the rows of *A*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In general, an (*n* − *j*)-dimensional face satisfies equality in *j* specific rows of *A*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] These rows form a **basis** of the face.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Geometrically speaking, this means that the face is the set of points on the polytope that lie in the intersection of *j* of the polytope's bounding hyperplanes.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The faces of a convex polytope thus form an Eulerian lattice called its **face lattice**, where the partial ordering is by set containment of faces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The definition of a face given above allows both the polytope itself and the empty set to be considered as faces, ensuring that every pair of faces has a join and a meet in the face lattice.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The whole polytope is the unique maximum element of the lattice, and the empty set, considered to be a (−1)-dimensional face (a **null polytope**) of every polytope, is the unique minimum element of the lattice.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Two polytopes are called **combinatorially isomorphic** if their face lattices are isomorphic.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The **polytope graph** (also **polytopal graph**, **edge graph**, **graph of the polytope** or **1-skeleton**) is the set of vertices and edges of the polytope only, ignoring higher-dimensional faces.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] For instance, a polyhedral graph is the polytope graph of a three-dimensional polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] By a result of Whitney the face lattice of a three-dimensional polytope is determined by its graph.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The same is true for simple polytopes of arbitrary dimension (Blind & Mani-Levitska 1987, proving a conjecture of Micha Perles).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Kalai (1988) gives a simple proof based on unique sink orientations.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Because these polytopes' face lattices are determined by their graphs, the problem of deciding whether two three-dimensional or simple convex polytopes are combinatorially isomorphic can be formulated equivalently as a special case of the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] However, it is also possible to translate these problems in the opposite direction, showing that polytope isomorphism testing is graph-isomorphism complete.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A convex polytope, like any compact convex subset of **R***n*, is homeomorphic to a closed ball.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Let *m* denote the dimension of the polytope.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] If the polytope is full-dimensional, then *m* = *n*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The convex polytope therefore is an *m*-dimensional manifold with boundary, its Euler characteristic is 1, and its fundamental group is trivial.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The boundary of the convex polytope is homeomorphic to an (*m* − 1)-sphere.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The boundary's Euler characteristic is 0 for even *m* and 2 for odd *m*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The boundary may also be regarded as a tessellation of (*m* − 1)-dimensional spherical space — i.e. as a spherical tiling.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A convex polytope can be decomposed into a simplicial complex, or union of simplices, satisfying certain properties.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Given a convex *r*-dimensional polytope *P*, a subset of its vertices containing (*r*+1) affinely independent points defines an *r*-simplex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] It is possible to form a collection of subsets such that the union of the corresponding simplices is equal to *P*, and the intersection of any two simplices is either empty or a lower-dimensional simplex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] This simplicial decomposition is the basis of many methods for computing the volume of a convex polytope, since the volume of a simplex is easily given by a formula.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Every regular convex polyhedron (Platonic solid) can be dissected into some even number of instances of its characteristic orthoscheme.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Different representations of a convex polytope have different utility, therefore the construction of one representation given another one is an important problem.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The problem of the construction of a V-representation is known as the vertex enumeration problem and the problem of the construction of a H-representation is known as the **facet enumeration problem**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] While the vertex set of a bounded convex polytope uniquely defines it, in various applications it is important to know more about the combinatorial structure of the polytope, i.e., about its face lattice.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] Various convex hull algorithms deal both with the facet enumeration and face lattice construction.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] In the planar case, i.e., for a convex polygon, both facet and vertex enumeration problems amount to ordering the vertices (resp. edges) around the convex hull.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] It is a trivial task when the convex polygon is specified in a traditional way for polygons, i.e., by the ordered sequence of its vertices $v_{1},\dots ,v_{m}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] When the input list of vertices (or edges) is unordered, the time complexity of the problems becomes O(*m* log *m*).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] A matching lower bound is known in the algebraic decision tree model of computation.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The task of computing the volume of a convex polytope has been studied in the field of computational geometry.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] The volume can be computed approximately, for instance, using the convex volume approximation technique, when having access to a membership oracle.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-polytope] As for exact computation, one obstacle is that, when given a representation of the convex polytope as an equation system of linear inequalities, the volume of the polytope may have a bit-length which is not polynomial in this representation.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] In geometry, a set of points is **convex** if it contains every line segment between two points in the set.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] For example, a solid cube is a convex set, but anything that is hollow or has an indent, such as a crescent shape, is not convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The boundary of a convex set in the plane is always a convex curve.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The intersection of all the convex sets that contain a given subset A of Euclidean space is called the convex hull of A.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] It is the smallest convex set containing A.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A convex function is a real-valued function defined on an interval with the property that its epigraph (the set of points on or above the graph of the function) is a convex set.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Convex minimization is a subfield of optimization that studies the problem of minimizing convex functions over convex sets.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The branch of mathematics devoted to the study of properties of convex sets and convex functions is called convex analysis.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Spaces in which convex sets are defined include the Euclidean spaces, the affine spaces over the real numbers, and certain non-Euclidean geometries.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Let S be a vector space or an affine space over the real numbers, or, more generally, over some ordered field (this includes Euclidean spaces, which are affine spaces).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A subset C of S is convex if, for all x and y in C, the line segment connecting x and y is included in C.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] This means that the affine combination (1 − *t*)*x* + *ty* belongs to C for all x,y in C and t in the interval [0, 1].
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] This implies that convexity is invariant under affine transformations.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Further, it implies that a convex set in a real or complex topological vector space is path-connected (and therefore also connected).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A set C is **strictly convex** if for every x and y in C, every point on the line segment connecting x and y other than the endpoints is inside the topological interior of C.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A closed convex subset is strictly convex if and only if every one of its boundary points is an extreme point.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A set C is absolutely convex if it is convex and balanced.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The convex subsets of **R** (the set of real numbers) are the intervals and the points of **R**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Some examples of convex subsets of the Euclidean plane are solid regular polygons, solid triangles, and intersections of solid triangles.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Some examples of convex subsets of a Euclidean 3-dimensional space are the Archimedean solids and the Platonic solids.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The Kepler-Poinsot polyhedra are examples of non-convex sets.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A set that is not convex is called a *non-convex set*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A polygon that is not a convex polygon is sometimes called a concave polygon, and some sources more generally use the term *concave set* to mean a non-convex set, but most authorities prohibit this usage.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The complement of a convex set, such as the epigraph of a concave function, is sometimes called a *reverse convex set*, especially in the context of mathematical optimization.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Given r points *u*1, ..., *ur* in a convex set S, and r nonnegative numbers *λ*1, ..., *λr* such that *λ*1 + ... + *λr* = 1, the affine combination $\sum _{k=1}^{r}\lambda _{k}u_{k}$ belongs to S.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] As the definition of a convex set is the case *r* = 2, this property characterizes convex sets.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Such an affine combination is called a convex combination of *u*1, ..., *ur*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The **convex hull** of a subset S of a real vector space is defined as the intersection of all convex sets that contain S.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] More concretely, the convex hull is the set of all convex combinations of points in S.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A *(bounded) convex polytope* is the convex hull of a finite subset of some Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The intersection of any collection of convex sets is convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The *union* of a collection of convex sets is convex if those sets form a chain (a totally ordered set) under inclusion.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] For this property, the restriction to chains is important, as the union of two convex sets need not be convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Closed convex sets are convex sets that contain all their limit points.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] They can be characterised as the intersections of *closed half-spaces* (sets of points in space that lie on and to one side of a hyperplane).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] From what has just been said, it is clear that such intersections are convex, and they will also be closed sets.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] To prove the converse, i.e., every closed convex set may be represented as such intersection, one needs the supporting hyperplane theorem in the form that for a given closed convex set C and point P outside it, there is a closed half-space H that contains C and not P.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The supporting hyperplane theorem is a special case of the Hahn–Banach theorem of functional analysis.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A **face** of a convex set C is a convex subset F of C such that whenever a point p in F lies strictly between two points x and y in C , both x and y must be in F .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Equivalently, for any $x,y\in C$ and any real number $0<t<1$ such that $(1-t)x+ty$ is in F , x and y must be in F .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] According to this definition, C itself and the empty set are faces of C ; these are sometimes called the *trivial faces* of C .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] An **extreme point** of C is a point that is a face of C .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Let C be a convex set in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ that is compact (or equivalently, closed and bounded).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Then C is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] More generally, each compact convex set in a locally convex topological vector space is the closed convex hull of its extreme points (the Krein–Milman theorem).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Let C be a convex body in the plane (a convex set whose interior is non-empty).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] We can inscribe a rectangle *r* in C such that a homothetic copy *R* of *r* is circumscribed about C.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The set ${\mathcal {K}}^{2}$ of all planar convex bodies can be parameterized in terms of the convex body diameter *D*, its inradius *r* (the biggest circle contained in the convex body) and its circumradius *R* (the smallest circle containing the convex body).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The image of this function is known a (*r*, *D*, *R*) Blachke-Santaló diagram.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Alternatively, the set ${\mathcal {K}}^{2}$ can also be parametrized by its width (the smallest distance between any two different parallel support hyperplanes), perimeter and area.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Let *X* be a topological vector space and $C\subseteq X$ be convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Every subset A of the vector space is contained within a smallest convex set (called the *convex hull* of A), namely the intersection of all convex sets containing A.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] For Minkowski addition, the *zero set* {0} containing only the zero vector 0 has special importance: For every non-empty subset S of a vector space $S+\{0\}=S;$ in algebraic terminology, {0} is the identity element of Minkowski addition (on the collection of non-empty sets).
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] In mathematical terminology, the operations of Minkowski summation and of forming convex hulls are commuting operations.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The Minkowski sum of two compact convex sets is compact.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The sum of a compact convex set and a closed convex set is closed.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The following famous theorem, proved by Dieudonné in 1966, gives a sufficient condition for the difference of two closed convex subsets to be closed.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] It uses the concept of a **recession cone** of a non-empty convex subset *S*, defined as: $\operatorname {rec} S=\left\{x\in X\,:\,x+S\subseteq S\right\},$ where this set is a convex cone containing $0\in X$ and satisfying $S+\operatorname {rec} S=S$ .
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The notion of convexity in the Euclidean space may be generalized by modifying the definition in some or other aspects.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The common name "generalized convexity" is used, because the resulting objects retain certain properties of convex sets.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Let C be a set in a real or complex vector space.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] C is **star convex (star-shaped)** if there exists an *x*0 in C such that the line segment from *x*0 to any point y in C is contained in C.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Hence a non-empty convex set is always star-convex but a star-convex set is not always convex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] An example of generalized convexity is **orthogonal convexity**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A set S in the Euclidean space is called **orthogonally convex** or **ortho-convex**, if any segment parallel to any of the coordinate axes connecting two points of S lies totally within S.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] It is easy to prove that an intersection of any collection of orthoconvex sets is orthoconvex.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Some other properties of convex sets are valid as well.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The definition of a convex set and a convex hull extends naturally to geometries which are not Euclidean by defining a geodesically convex set to be one that contains the geodesics joining any two points in the set.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Convexity can be extended for a totally ordered set X endowed with the order topology.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The subspace Y is a convex set if for each pair of points *a*, *b* in Y such that *a* ≤ *b*, the interval [*a*, *b*] = {*x* ∈ *X* | *a* ≤ *x* ≤ *b*} is contained in Y.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] That is, Y is convex if and only if for all *a*, *b* in Y, *a* ≤ *b* implies [*a*, *b*] ⊆ *Y*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] A convex set is *not* connected in general: a counter-example is given by the subspace {1,2,3} in **Z**, which is both convex and not connected.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The notion of convexity may be generalised to other objects, if certain properties of convexity are selected as axioms.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The intersection of any collection from *𝒞* is in *𝒞*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The union of a chain (with respect to the inclusion relation) of elements of *𝒞* is in *𝒞*.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] The elements of *𝒞* are called convex sets and the pair (*X*, *𝒞*) is called a **convexity space**.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] For the ordinary convexity, the first two axioms hold, and the third one is trivial.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] For an alternative definition of abstract convexity, more suited to discrete geometry, see the *convex geometries* associated with antimatroids.
[src:convex-geometry/convex-set] Convexity can be generalised as an abstract algebraic structure: a space is convex if it is possible to take convex combinations of points.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Let *X*1, ..., *Xn* be a finite collection of convex subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , with $n\geq d+1$ .
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Let $\{X_{\alpha }\}$ be a collection of compact convex subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , such that every subcollection of cardinality at most $d+1$ has nonempty intersection.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Then the whole collection has nonempty intersection.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] We prove the finite version, using Radon's theorem as in the proof by Radon (1921).
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Note that the only element of A that may not be in *Xj* is *xj*.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Since *Xj* is convex, it then also contains the convex hull of *A*2 and therefore also *p* ∈ *Xj*.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Likewise, if *xj* ∉ *A*1, then *Xj* ⊃ *A*1, and by the same reasoning *p* ∈ *Xj*.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Since p is in every *Xj*, it must also be in the intersection.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Above, we have assumed that the points *x*1, ..., *xn* are all distinct.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] If this is not the case, say *xi* = *xk* for some *i* ≠ *k*, then *xi* is in every one of the sets *Xj*, and again we conclude that the intersection is nonempty.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] This completes the proof in the case *n* = *d* + 2.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Since the intersection of convex sets is convex, every non-empty finite intersection of elements of ${\mathcal {U}}$ is contractible.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] By the basic nerve lemma, X is homotopy equivalent to the geometric realization $|{\mathcal {N}}|$ of the nerve ${\mathcal {N}}$ of the cover.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] $X_{1}\cap \cdots \cap X_{n+2}=\varnothing ,$ the nerve ${\mathcal {N}}$ is the boundary complex of the simplex $\Delta ^{n+1}$ consisting of all the n -faces.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Therefore $|{\mathcal {N}}|$ is homeomorphic to $S^{n}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] It follows that $H_{n}(X)\cong H_{n}(S^{n})\cong \mathbb {Z} .$ This is a contradiction, since X is a non-compact n -dimensional manifold, and the top homology group of a non-compact manifold is zero.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] The **colorful Helly theorem** is an extension of Helly's theorem in which, instead of one collection, there are *d*+1 collections of convex subsets of **R***d*.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] If, for *every* choice of a *transversal* – one set from every collection – there is a point in common to all the chosen sets, then for *at least one* of the collections, there is a point in common to all sets in the collection.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Figuratively, one can consider the *d*+1 collections to be of *d*+1 different colors.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] Then the theorem says that, if every choice of one-set-per-color has a non-empty intersection, then there exists a color such that all sets of that color have a non-empty intersection.
[src:convex-geometry/helly-s-theorem] For every *a* > 0 there is some *b* > 0 such that, if *X*1, ..., *Xn* are *n* convex subsets of **R***d*, and at least an *a*-fraction of (*d*+1)-tuples of the sets have a point in common, then a fraction of at least *b* of the sets have a point in common.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] In geometry, the **Minkowski sum** of two subsets A and B of a Euclidean space is the set of the points whose position vectors form the sumset of the position vectors of A and B.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] The Minkowski sum depends on the choice of an origin in the Euclidean space.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] As a change of origin amounts to translate the Minkowski sum, the Minkowski sum is defined up to a translation, and its shape and orientation are well defined.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] The **Minkowski difference** (also *Minkowski subtraction*, *Minkowski decomposition*, or *geometric difference*) is the corresponding inverse, where ${\textstyle (A-B)}$ produces a set that could be summed with *B* to recover *A*.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] This is defined as the complement of the Minkowski sum of the complement of *A* with the reflection of *B* about the origin.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] This definition allows a symmetrical relationship between the Minkowski sum and difference.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Note that alternately taking the sum and difference with *B* is not necessarily equivalent.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] The sum can fill gaps which the difference may not re-open, and the difference can erase small islands which the sum cannot recreate from nothing.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] In 2D image processing the Minkowski sum and difference are known as dilation and erosion.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] An alternative definition of the Minkowski difference is sometimes used for computing intersection of convex shapes.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] This is not equivalent to the previous definition, and is not an inverse of the sum operation.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Instead it replaces the vector addition of the Minkowski sum with a vector subtraction.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] If the two convex shapes intersect, the resulting set will contain the origin.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] The concept is named for Hermann Minkowski.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] which comprises the vertices of a hexagon and its center.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] For another example, consider the Minkowski sums of open or closed balls in the field ${\textstyle \mathbb {K} ,}$ which is either the real numbers ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} }$ or complex numbers ${\textstyle \mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] The Minkowski sum of a closed ball and an open ball is an open ball.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] More generally, the Minkowski sum of an open subset with *any* other set will be an open subset.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] This shows that the Minkowski sum of two closed sets is not necessarily a closed set.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] However, the Minkowski sum of two closed subsets will be a closed subset if at least one of these sets is also a compact subset.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] for every ${\textstyle \mu ,\lambda \geq 0}$ .
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Conversely, if this "distributive property" holds for all non-negative real numbers, ${\textstyle \mu }$ and ${\textstyle \lambda }$ , then the set is convex.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums act linearly on the perimeter of two-dimensional convex bodies: the perimeter of the sum equals the sum of perimeters.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Additionally, if ${\textstyle K}$ is (the interior of) a curve of constant width, then the Minkowski sum of ${\textstyle K}$ and of its 180° rotation is a disk.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] These two facts can be combined to give a short proof of Barbier's theorem on the perimeter of curves of constant width.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Minkowski addition plays a central role in mathematical morphology.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] It arises in the brush-and-stroke paradigm of 2D computer graphics (with various uses, notably by Donald E.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Knuth in Metafont), and as the solid sweep operation of 3D computer graphics.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] It has also been shown to be closely connected to the Earth mover's distance, and by extension, optimal transport.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums are used in motion planning of an object among obstacles.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] They are used for the computation of the configuration space, which is the set of all admissible positions of the object.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] In numerical control machining, the programming of the NC tool exploits the fact that the Minkowski sum of the cutting piece with its trajectory gives the shape of the cut in the material.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] In OpenSCAD Minkowski sums are used to outline a shape with another shape creating a composite of both shapes.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums are also frequently used in aggregation theory when individual objects to be aggregated are characterized via sets.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Minkowski sums, specifically Minkowski differences, are often used alongside GJK algorithms to compute collision detection for convex hulls in physics engines.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] For two convex polygons *P* and *Q* in the plane with *m* and *n* vertices, their Minkowski sum is a convex polygon with at most *m* + *n* vertices and may be computed in time O(*m* + *n*) by a very simple procedure, which may be informally described as follows.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Assume that the edges of a polygon are given and the direction, say, counterclockwise, along the polygon boundary.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Then it is easily seen that these edges of the convex polygon are ordered by polar angle.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Let us merge the ordered sequences of the directed edges from *P* and *Q* into a single ordered sequence *S*.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Imagine that these edges are solid arrows which can be moved freely while keeping them parallel to their original direction.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] Assemble these arrows in the order of the sequence *S* by attaching the tail of the next arrow to the head of the previous arrow.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] It turns out that the resulting polygonal chain will in fact be a convex polygon which is the Minkowski sum of *P* and *Q*.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] If one polygon is convex and another one is not, the complexity of their Minkowski sum is O(*nm*).
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] If both of them are nonconvex, their Minkowski sum complexity is O((*mn*)2).
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] There is also a notion of the **essential Minkowski sum** +e of two subsets of Euclidean space.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] where *μ* denotes the *n*-dimensional Lebesgue measure.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] where "ess sup" denotes the essential supremum.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] By the Minkowski inequality, the function *hK+pL* is again positive homogeneous and convex and hence the support function of a compact convex set.
[src:convex-geometry/minkowski-addition] This definition is fundamental in the *L**p* Brunn-Minkowski theory.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] Here, a closed half-space is the half-space that includes the points within the hyperplane.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] Conversely, if S is a closed set with nonempty interior such that every point on the boundary has a supporting hyperplane, then S is a convex set, and is the intersection of all its supporting closed half-spaces.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] The hyperplane in the theorem may not be unique, as noticed in the second picture on the right.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] If the closed set S is not convex, the statement of the theorem is not true at all points on the boundary of $S,$ as illustrated in the third picture on the right.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] The supporting hyperplanes of convex sets are also called **tac-planes** or **tac-hyperplanes**.
[src:convex-geometry/supporting-hyperplane] The forward direction can be proved as a special case of the separating hyperplane theorem (see the page for the proof).
